{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"a0ccf42d-759f-4a92-a158-e06d6121ab5e","content":"Here's a complete migration plan for moving your 5 MSTest projects from VSTest to Microsoft.Testing.Platform (MTP):\n\n---\n\n## Migration Plan: VSTest → Microsoft.Testing.Platform\n\n### Phase 1 — Update Packages\n\nIn each test `.csproj`, replace your current package references:\n\n```xml\n<!-- REMOVE these -->\n<PackageReference Include=\"MSTest.TestFramework\" Version=\"3.8.0\" />\n<PackageReference Include=\"MSTest.TestAdapter\" Version=\"3.8.0\" />\n<PackageReference Include=\"Microsoft.NET.Test.Sdk\" Version=\"17.13.0\" />\n\n<!-- REPLACE with single meta-package -->\n<PackageReference Include=\"MSTest\" Version=\"3.8.0\" />\n```\n\nThen enable MTP by adding this property (ideally in `Directory.Build.props` so it applies to all 5 projects):\n\n```xml\n<PropertyGroup>\n  <EnableMSTestRunner>true</EnableMSTestRunner>\n  <OutputType>Exe</OutputType>\n  <TestingPlatformDotnetTestSupport>true</TestingPlatformDotnetTestSupport>\n</PropertyGroup>\n```\n\n`TestingPlatformDotnetTestSupport` ensures `dotnet test` works with MTP (bridges the new runner to the familiar CLI).\n\n---\n\n### Phase 2 — TRX Reporting\n\nMTP doesn't emit TRX by default. Add the extension:\n\n```xml\n<PackageReference Include=\"Microsoft.Testing.Extensions.TrxReport\" Version=\"1.6.2\" />\n```\n\nEnable it in your CI via an `.runsettings` file or command-line:\n\n```\ndotnet test --report-trx --results-directory $(Build.ArtifactStagingDirectory)/TestResults\n```\n\n---\n\n### Phase 3 — Code Coverage\n\nReplace the VSTest built-in coverage with the MTP-compatible collector:\n\n```xml\n<PackageReference Include=\"Microsoft.Testing.Extensions.CodeCoverage\" Version=\"17.13.0\" />\n```\n\nRun with:\n\n```\ndotnet test --collect \"Code Coverage\"\n```\n\nOr for Cobertura output (common for Azure DevOps reporting):\n\n```\ndotnet test --collect \"Code Coverage;Format=Cobertura\"\n```\n\n---\n\n### Phase 4 — Azure DevOps Pipeline Changes\n\nReplace the `VSTest@3` task:\n\n```yaml\n# BEFORE\n- task: VSTest@3\n  inputs:\n    testAssemblies: '**/*Tests.dll'\n    codeCoverageEnabled: true\n\n# AFTER\n- task: DotNetCoreCLI@2\n  displayName: 'Run Tests'\n  inputs:\n    command: test\n    projects: '**/*Tests.csproj'\n    arguments: >-\n      --report-trx\n      --results-directory $(Agent.TempDirectory)/TestResults\n      --collect \"Code Coverage;Format=Cobertura\"\n\n- task: PublishTestResults@2\n  displayName: 'Publish TRX Results'\n  condition: always()\n  inputs:\n    testResultsFormat: VSTest\n    testResultsFiles: '$(Agent.TempDirectory)/TestResults/**/*.trx'\n\n- task: PublishCodeCoverageResults@2\n  displayName: 'Publish Coverage'\n  inputs:\n    summaryFileLocation: '$(Agent.TempDirectory)/TestResults/**/coverage.cobertura.xml'\n```\n\n---\n\n### Phase 5 — Validate Locally\n\n```bash\ndotnet test --report-trx --collect \"Code Coverage\" -- RunConfiguration.ResultsDirectory=./TestResults\n```\n\nConfirm:\n- All tests discovered and pass\n- `.trx` files generated\n- Coverage files generated\n\n---\n\n### Key Differences to Be Aware Of\n\n| Concern | Notes |\n|---------|-------|\n| **Parallel execution** | MTP runs each test project as its own executable; parallelism across projects comes from `dotnet test`. Within-project parallelism is controlled by MSTest settings as before. |\n| **Filters** | `--filter` still works identically. |\n| **runsettings** | Still supported via `--settings file.runsettings`. |\n| **Platform extensions** | MTP uses an extension model — TRX and coverage are extensions you opt into (packages above). |\n| **Executable output** | Test projects become executables (`OutputType=Exe`). This is expected and required. |\n\n---\n\n### Recommended Order\n\n1. Create a branch, add `Directory.Build.props` changes\n2. Update one test project first, verify locally\n3. Roll out to remaining 4 projects\n4. Update the pipeline YAML\n5. Verify TRX + covera